+## Allowances
+
+Allowances are the mirror of timed locks. Where `lock` blocks a list for a duration, `allow` lets you use a list freely for a duration, after which it auto-blocks. This is great for "let me scroll social media for 20 minutes, then I'm done" sessions.
+
+Let's try starting an allowance on our list by running `freeblock allow [list] [duration]`. I'll allow 20 minutes.
+
+> Make sure to provide the duration in a supported format: `HH:MM:SS`, `HH:MM`, or shorthand like `20m`, `1h`, `1h20m`, `90s`.
+
+After you confirm, the list is unblocked and you can use the apps in it. If you now run `freeblock status`, the list will appear as disabled with a `⏳ ... remaining` annotation showing the time left in your allowance.
+
+When the duration runs out, FreeBlock automatically transitions the list into a manual block. The list is now active and the apps will close. You can clear this block at any time with the regular `freeblock unblock` command.
+
+> Note: running `freeblock block`, `freeblock unblock`, or `freeblock lock` on a list with an active allowance will cancel the allowance immediately. Running `freeblock allow` on a list with an active allowance will replace it with a new one (the timer resets).
+
 ## Creating Schedules
 
 Schedules enable lists automatically in certain time periods. Let's try creating one in order to block distracting apps and websites at night. To do that, we will use the `freeblock schedule add [name] [lists] [start] [end] [days]` command.
